amsci termed "interregnum," an in-between time in which "the old [order] is dying and the new cannot be born." The recoding of history as literary form provides occasions for reconsidering modern conceptualizations of aesthetic experience, mood, temporality, thought, politics, ethical experience, as well as of literature itself as social institution. In his analysis, Patrick Dove seeks to create dialogues between literature and theoretical perspectives, including Continental philosophy, political thought, psychoanalysis, and sociology of globalization. The author highlights the connections between mass media, technology, politics, and economics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aLiterature and globalization. 0aLiterature and societyxLatin AmericaxLatin AmericaxCriticism, interpretation, etc. 0aLiterature and societyzLatin America. 0aSovereignty in literature. 0aSpanish American literaturexHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aSpanish American literaturexHistory and criticismx21st century. 0aSpanish American literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSpanish American literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Literature. 4aPolitics and Law : Politics. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2016z978311149098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438461564423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438461564/original  a978-3-11-149098-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles